  "prompt": "How did English become the official language of so many countries?",
  "response": "The widespread adoption of English as an official language can be traced back to the British Empire's global colonization efforts from the 17th to 20th centuries. As Britain established colonies across the globe in regions like North America, Africa, Asia, and Oceania, they imposed their language and administrative systems.\n\nKey factors in English's global spread include:\n\n1. British colonization\n- Established English-speaking governments and educational systems\n- Forced English as the language of administration and commerce\n\n2. United States' global influence\n- Economic and cultural power after World War II\n- Spread of American media, technology, and business practices\n\n3. Globalization\n- English became the lingua franca of international business\n- Used in scientific research, diplomacy, and technology\n- Adopted as a common language for international communication\n\n4. Economic advantages\n- Knowledge of English often associated with better job opportunities\n- Many multinational corporations use English as their primary language\n\n5. Cultural exportation\n- Hollywood movies\n- Popular music\n- Internet content\n\nCountries like India, Nigeria, Singapore, and many Caribbean nations retained English as an official language after gaining independence, reflecting its embedded administrative and educational role.\n\nToday, English is an official language in approximately 67 countries and is spoken by over 1.5 billion people worldwide, making it the most widely spoken language globally.",
